ng steps in natural language to achieve it.\nIn addition, try to give advice to avoid syntax error.\nAn SystemVerilog module always starts with a line starting with the keyword \'module\' followed by the module name.\nIt ends with the keyword \'endmodule\'.\n\nBelow is the golden testbench code for the module generated with the given natural language specification.\n<golden_testbench>\n`timescale 1 ps/1 ps\n`define OK 12\n`define INCORRECT 13\n\n\nmodule stimulus_gen (\n\tinput clk,\n\toutput reg a, b,\n\toutput reg[511:0] wavedrom_title,\n\toutput reg wavedrom_enable\n);\n\n\n// Add two ports to module stimulus_gen:\n//    output [511:0] wavedrom_title\n//    output reg wavedrom_enable\n\n\ttask wavedrom_start(input[511:0] title = "");\n\tendtask\n\t\n\ttask wavedrom_stop;\n\t\t#1;\n\tendtask\t\n\n\n\n\tinitial begin\n\t\tint count; count = 0;\n\t\t{a,b} <= 1\'b0;\n\t\twavedrom_start("NOR gate");\n\t\trepeat(10) @(posedge clk)\n\t\t\t{a,b} <= count++;\t\t\n\t\twavedrom_stop();\n\t\t\n\t\trepeat(200) @(posedge clk, negedge clk)\n\t\t\t{b,a} <= $random;\n\t\t\t\n\t\t#1 $finish;\n\tend\n\t\nendmodule\n\nmodule tb();\n\n\ttypedef struct packed {\n\t\tint errors;\n\t\tint errortime;\n\t\tint errors_out;\n\t\tint errortime_out;\n\n\t\tint clocks;\n\t} stats;\n\t\n\tstats stats1;\n\t\n\t\n\twire[511:0] wavedrom_title;\n\twire wavedrom_enable;\n\tint wavedrom_hide_after_time;\n\t\n\treg clk=0;\n\tinitial forever\n\t\t#5 clk = ~clk;\n\n\tlogic a;\n\tlogic b;\n\tlogic out_ref;\n\tlogic out_dut;\n\n\tinitial begin \n\t\t$dumpfile("wave.vcd");\n\t\t$dumpvars(1, stim1.clk, tb_mismatch ,a,b,out_ref,out_dut );\n\tend\n\n\n\twire tb_match;\t\t// Verification\n\twire tb_mismatch = ~tb_match;\n\t\n\tstimulus_gen stim1 (\n\t\t.clk,\n\t\t.* ,\n\t\t.a,\n\t\t.b );\n\tRefModule good1 (\n\t\t.a,\n\t\t.b,\n\t\t.out(out_ref) );\n\t\t\n\tTopModule top_module1 (\n\t\t.a,\n\t\t.b,\n\t\t.out(out_dut) );\n\n\t\n\tbit strobe = 0;\n\ttask wait_for_end_of_timestep;\n\t\trepeat(5) begin\n\t\t\tstrobe <= !strobe;  // Try to delay until the very end of the time step.\n\t\t\t@(strobe);\n\t\tend\n\tendtask\t\n\n\t\n\tfinal begin\n\t\tif (stats1.errors_out) $display("Hint: Output \'%s\' has %0d mismatches. First mismatch occurred at time %0d.", "out", stats1.errors_out, stats1.errortime_out);\n\t\telse $display("Hint: Output \'%s\' has no mismatches.", "out");\n\n\t\t$display("Hint: Total mismatched samples is %1d out of %1d samples\\n", stats1.errors, stats1.clocks);\n\t\t$display("Simulation finished at %0d ps", $time);\n\t\t$display("Mismatches: %1d in %1d samples", stats1.errors, stats1.clocks);\n\tend\n\t\n\t// Verification: XORs on the right makes any X in good_vector match anything, but X in dut_vector will only match X.\n\tassign tb_match = ( { out_ref } === ( { out_ref } ^ { out_dut } ^ { out_ref } ) );\n\t// Use explicit sensitivity list here. @(*) causes NetProc::nex_input() to be called when trying to compute\n\t// the sensitivity list of the @(strobe) process, which isn\'t implemented.\n\talways @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\n\t\tstats1.clocks++;\n\t\tif (!tb_match) begin\n\t\t\tif (stats1.errors == 0) stats1.errortime = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors++;\n\t\tend\n\t\tif (out_ref !== ( out_ref ^ out_dut ^ out_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_out == 0) stats1.errortime_out = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors_out = stats1.errors_out+1\'b1; end\n\n\tend\n\n   // add timeout after 100K cycles\n   initial begin\n     #1000000\n     $display("TIMEOUT");\n     $finish();\n   end\n\nendmodule\n\n\n<golden_testbench>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.ASSISTANT: 'assistant'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='{\n    "reasoning": "The user requires two main deliverables: an IO interface matching the specification derived from the golden testbench, and an improved golden testbench. \\n\\n**1. Interface Generation:**\\nThe input specification defines `TopModule` with ports `input a`, `input b`, `output out`. However, the provided `golden_testbench` instantiates `TopModule` as `TopModule top_module1 ( .a, .b, .out(out_dut) );`. Since the golden testbench is the ultimate authority for structure, I must define the interface based on the signals used in the testbench for `TopModule`, which are `a`, `b`, and `out`.\\n\\n**2. Testbench Improvement:**\\nThe golden testbench needs significant enhancement to meet the new requirements:\\n    a. **Error Reporting:** The final display must be changed from the existing \'Hint\' structure to the required \'SIMULATION PASSED\' or \'SIMULATION FAILED - x MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME y\'.\\n    b. **First Mismatch Display:** When a mismatch occurs for the first time, the inputs (`a`, `b`), output signals (`out_dut` - DUT output, `out_ref` - expected output), and expected output (`out_ref`) must be displayed at that time.\\n    c. **Signal Display Format:** For multi-bit signals (though `a`, `b`, `out` are single-bit in the spec, the existing testbench uses wider signals like `wavedrom_title`), if they were multi-bit, they should be displayed in HEX and BIN formats if their width is $\\\\le 64$. Since `a`, `b`, and `out` are single-bit, this mainly applies to the existing wide signals in the testbench.\\n    d. **Functionality Preservation:** The core logic, including error counting (`stats1.errors` and `stats1.errors_out`), must remain intact.\\n\\n**Implementation Steps:**\\n1. **Interface:** Define the minimal interface for `TopModule` based on the testbench usage: `input a, b; output out;`.\\n2. **Testbench Modification:**\\n    a. **Signal Declaration:** Ensure all necessary signals (`a`, `b`, `out_ref`, `out_dut`, etc.) are present and correctly typed.\\n    b. **Error Tracking:** Capture the timing and values upon the *first* mismatch for both `tb_mismatch` and `errors_out`.\\n    c. **Display Logic:** Replace the `final` block with the required pass/fail logic. \\n    d. **First Mismatch Logging:** Inside the `always @(posedge clk, negedge clk)` block, if `stats1.errors == 0` when `!tb_match` is true, log the state (`a`, `b`, `out_dut`, `out_ref`) at `$time`.\\n    e. **Clock/Timing:** Maintain the existing clock generation and stimulus sequence.\\n\\n**Syntax Advice:**\\n- Use `logic` type for signals where possible for cleaner assignment, although the original used `reg` and `wire`. I will stick closely to the original structure but ensure consistency.\\n- In the `final` block, I must handle the case where `stats1.errors` or `stats1.errors_out` is zero to print "   \n    ,\n    "The golden testbench heavily relies on external modules (`RefModule`, `stimulus_gen`) and specific timing sequences. I must ensure the new error reporting logic correctly hooks into the existing `stats1` structure and correctly interprets the mismatch conditions (`tb_mismatch` and `out_ref !== ( out_ref ^ out_dut ^ out_ref )`).\\n\\nI will modify the `always` block to capture the state upon the *first* error occurrence for detailed display, and then modify the `final` block for the final summary message as requested.\\n\\n**Refinement on First Mismatch Display:** The requirement is to display inputs, output signals, and expected output signals at the time of the first mismatch. This needs to happen inside the `always` block when `stats1.errors` transitions from 0 to 1, or when `stats1.errors_out` transitions from 0 to 1. I will implement a dedicated capture for the first time a mismatch occurs overall (using `stats1.errors`).\\n\\n**Interface Correction:** Although the testbench uses complex stimulus generation, the interface for the DUT (`TopModule`) is simply $a, b, out$. I will generate the interface strictly for `TopModule` based on this usage, using `logic` as requested for port declarations where appropriate, although the golden testbench uses `logic` for internal signals, it declares the ports implicitly via the instantiation connection. I will define the interface using standard SystemVerilog types (logic).\\n\\nSince the 